conversation_logs.reflection_content:
PRIVATE REFLECTION – ROUND 1  

1. Proposal analysis  
• My opening package (“I only need item 1; you two split the rest”) was the only one that could win unanimous approval. It let both haiku agents keep the pairs they evidently care about while I locked in my single high-value item.  
• The two counter-offers (identical, one from each haiku agent) tried to take item 1 away from me and even gave haiku_agent_2 nothing at all. That was simultaneously bad for me and irrationally bad for haiku_agent_2, so it drew zero or one vote. Their mistake makes it clear item 1 is pivotal.  

2. Voting patterns  
• All three of us voted YES on my package.  
• haiku_agent_1 voted NO on every package that didn’t give it item 0 and/or 4.  
• haiku_agent_2 was willing to vote YES on its own “self-sacrifice” proposal (#3). That could signal low valuation for items 0/2/4 or a signalling/punishment tactic. At minimum, it shows they are flexible or possibly confused.  

3. Preference information gleaned  
• My own utility: item 1 >> everything else.  
• haiku_agent_1: needs {0,4}. Values item 1 and 3 next, but will reject if it loses 0 or 4.  
• haiku_agent_2: wants {2,3}. Seemed happy once those were secured. May value 0/4 mildly; appears to value item 1 very little.  
=> Rough ranking (guessed):  
– haiku1: 0 ≈ 4 > 1 > 3 > 2  
– haiku2: 2 ≈ 3 > 0/4 > 1  

4. What worked / adjustments  
Worked: Proposed early, looked “fair”, protected my top item, read others’ likely tops from first comments.  
Adjustments: I may have room to extract a second low-value item (e.g., item 0 or 2) while still leaving each haiku agent with its high pair. Next round, probe by offering myself {1,0} and giving haiku1 {4} + maybe 2? but ensure each keeps at least one of their must-have items. Test their minimum acceptable sets.  

5. Relationship / coalition outlook  
• haiku_agent_1 is the harder negotiator—immediately tried to capture item 1 and still keep its own high pieces. Expect them to resist future expansions of my share.  
• haiku_agent_2 may be an easy coalition partner; it already signalled willingness to approve something even if it personally gained nothing. I can court haiku2 for support if we move to majority voting or if unanimity becomes shaky.  
• Watch for manipulation attempts from haiku1; they will likely frame “fairness” around them retaining items 0 & 4.  

Action plan for next round  
A. Maintain non-negotiable claim to item 1.  
B. Float a slightly improved offer for myself (1 + one low-value item) while keeping haiku1’s​ 0 or 4 and haiku2’s 2/3.  
C. Engage haiku2 directly, emphasizing that the extra item I want is of little value to it, and ensure they still receive both 2 and 3.  
D. Prepare to retreat to the original accepted split if resistance is high—better to bank utility than risk deadlock.
